    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-09-01T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-09-01T14:00:00-05:00" n="361"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d361">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/10266: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-09-01T15:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 1, 1920—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1438. B–105. For Boyden.</p>
                <p>Your B–189, August 5.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Paragraph 2. Department wishes to be kept fully informed in regard to
                        bonds issued by Germany in connection with coal advances. Information is
                        especially desired on plans to guarantee and negotiate these bonds. Why does
                        England intend to hold her share? To the extent that these bonds shall be
                        repaid by Germany before May 1, 1921, amount should be deducted from twenty
                        milliards stipulated in Article 235. Consistent attitude of this Government
                        should be that Germany cannot be called upon to pay total of more than this
                        amount under any circumstances.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Paragraph 3. Department agrees that Germany is free to utilize for payment
                        of advances any assets available. With regard to implication in your formal
                        statement that position of United States is <pb facs="0520" n="430"
                            xml:id="pg_430"/> not affected by terms of Spa protocol, our views are
                        fully stated in our answer to your B182 and B173.<note n="85"
                            xml:id="d361fn85">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_415">pp. 415</ref> and
                                <ref target="#pg_403">403</ref>, respectively.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
